[src:java/classes] The introduction to object-oriented concepts in the lesson titled Object-oriented Programming Concepts used a bicycle class as an example, with racing bikes, mountain bikes, and tandem bikes as subclasses.
[src:java/classes] Here is sample code for a possible implementation of a `Bicycle` class, to give you an overview of a class declaration.
[src:java/classes] Subsequent sections of this lesson will back up and explain class declarations step by step.
[src:java/classes] For the moment, don't concern yourself with the details.
[src:java/classes] `MountainBike` inherits all the fields and methods of `Bicycle` and adds the field `seatHeight` and a method to set it (mountain bikes have seats that can be moved up and down as the terrain demands).
[src:java/concepts-index] If you've never used an object-oriented programming language before, you'll need to learn a few basic concepts before you can begin writing any code.
[src:java/concepts-index] This lesson will introduce you to objects, classes, inheritance, interfaces, and packages.
[src:java/concepts-index] Each discussion focuses on how these concepts relate to the real world, while simultaneously providing an introduction to the syntax of the Java programming language.
[src:java/concepts-index] An object is a software bundle of related state and behavior.
[src:java/concepts-index] Software objects are often used to model the real-world objects that you find in everyday life.
[src:java/concepts-index] This lesson explains how state and behavior are represented within an object, introduces the concept of data encapsulation, and explains the benefits of designing your software in this manner.
[src:java/concepts-index] A class is a blueprint or prototype from which objects are created.
[src:java/concepts-index] This section defines a class that models the state and behavior of a real-world object.
[src:java/concepts-index] It intentionally focuses on the basics, showing how even a simple class can cleanly model state and behavior.
[src:java/concepts-index] Inheritance provides a powerful and natural mechanism for organizing and structuring your software.
[src:java/concepts-index] This section explains how classes inherit state and behavior from their superclasses, and explains how to derive one class from another using the simple syntax provided by the Java programming language.
[src:java/concepts-index] An interface is a contract between a class and the outside world.
[src:java/concepts-index] When a class implements an interface, it promises to provide the behavior published by that interface.
[src:java/concepts-index] This section defines a simple interface and explains the necessary changes for any class that implements it.
[src:java/concepts-index] A package is a namespace for organizing classes and interfaces in a logical manner.
[src:java/concepts-index] Placing your code into packages makes large software projects easier to manage.
[src:java/concepts-index] This section explains why this is useful, and introduces you to the Application Programming Interface (API) provided by the Java platform.
[src:java/concepts-index] Use the questions and exercises presented in this section to test your understanding of objects, classes, inheritance, interfaces, and packages.
[src:java/createinterface] There are a number of situations in software engineering when it is important for disparate groups of programmers to agree to a "contract" that spells out how their software interacts.
[src:java/createinterface] Each group should be able to write their code without any knowledge of how the other group's code is written.
[src:java/createinterface] Generally speaking, *interfaces* are such contracts.
[src:java/createinterface] For example, imagine a futuristic society where computer-controlled robotic cars transport passengers through city streets without a human operator.
[src:java/createinterface] Automobile manufacturers write software (Java, of course) that operates the automobile—stop, start, accelerate, turn left, and so forth.
[src:java/createinterface] Another industrial group, electronic guidance instrument manufacturers, make computer systems that receive GPS (Global Positioning System) position data and wireless transmission of traffic conditions and use that information to drive the car.
[src:java/createinterface] The auto manufacturers must publish an industry-standard interface that spells out in detail what methods can be invoked to make the car move (any car, from any manufacturer).
[src:java/createinterface] The guidance manufacturers can then write software that invokes the methods described in the interface to command the car.
[src:java/createinterface] Neither industrial group needs to know *how* the other group's software is implemented.
[src:java/createinterface] In fact, each group considers its software highly proprietary and reserves the right to modify it at any time, as long as it continues to adhere to the published interface.
[src:java/createinterface] In the Java programming language, an *interface* is a reference type, similar to a class, that can contain *only* constants, method signatures, default methods, static methods, and nested types.
[src:java/createinterface] Method bodies exist only for default methods and static methods.
[src:java/createinterface] Interfaces cannot be instantiated—they can only be *implemented* by classes or *extended* by other interfaces.
[src:java/createinterface] Extension is discussed later in this lesson.
[src:java/createinterface] Note that the method signatures have no braces and are terminated with a semicolon.
[src:java/createinterface] To use an interface, you write a class that *implements* the interface.
[src:java/createinterface] When an instantiable class implements an interface, it provides a method body for each of the methods declared in the interface.
[src:java/createinterface] In the robotic car example above, it is the automobile manufacturers who will implement the interface.
[src:java/createinterface] Chevrolet's implementation will be substantially different from that of Toyota, of course, but both manufacturers will adhere to the same interface.
[src:java/createinterface] The guidance manufacturers, who are the clients of the interface, will build systems that use GPS data on a car's location, digital street maps, and traffic data to drive the car.
[src:java/createinterface] In so doing, the guidance systems will invoke the interface methods: turn, change lanes, brake, accelerate, and so forth.
[src:java/createinterface] The robotic car example shows an interface being used as an industry standard *Application Programming Interface (API)*.
[src:java/createinterface] APIs are also common in commercial software products.
[src:java/createinterface] Typically, a company sells a software package that contains complex methods that another company wants to use in its own software product.
[src:java/createinterface] An example would be a package of digital image processing methods that are sold to companies making end-user graphics programs.
[src:java/createinterface] The image processing company writes its classes to implement an interface, which it makes public to its customers.
[src:java/createinterface] The graphics company then invokes the image processing methods using the signatures and return types defined in the interface.
[src:java/createinterface] While the image processing company's API is made public (to its customers), its implementation of the API is kept as a closely guarded secret—in fact, it may revise the implementation at a later date as long as it continues to implement the original interface that its customers have relied on.
[src:java/datatypes] The Java programming language is statically-typed, which means that all variables must first be declared before they can be used.
[src:java/datatypes] Doing so tells your program that a field named "gear" exists, holds numerical data, and has an initial value of "1".
[src:java/datatypes] A variable's data type determines the values it may contain, plus the operations that may be performed on it.
[src:java/datatypes] In addition to `int`, the Java programming language supports seven other *primitive data types*.
[src:java/datatypes] A primitive type is predefined by the language and is named by a reserved keyword.
[src:java/datatypes] Primitive values do not share state with other primitive values.
[src:java/datatypes] In addition to the eight primitive data types listed above, the Java programming language also provides special support for character strings via the java.lang.String class.
[src:java/datatypes] Enclosing your character string within double quotes will automatically create a new `String` object; for example, `String s = "this is a string";`.
[src:java/datatypes] `String` objects are *immutable*, which means that once created, their values cannot be changed.
[src:java/datatypes] The `String` class is not technically a primitive data type, but considering the special support given to it by the language, you'll probably tend to think of it as such.
[src:java/datatypes] It's not always necessary to assign a value when a field is declared.
[src:java/datatypes] Fields that are declared but not initialized will be set to a reasonable default by the compiler.
[src:java/datatypes] Generally speaking, this default will be zero or `null`, depending on the data type.
[src:java/datatypes] Relying on such default values, however, is generally considered bad programming style.
[src:java/datatypes] The following chart summarizes the default values for the above data types.
[src:java/datatypes] Local variables are slightly different; the compiler never assigns a default value to an uninitialized local variable.
[src:java/datatypes] If you cannot initialize your local variable where it is declared, make sure to assign it a value before you attempt to use it.
[src:java/datatypes] Accessing an uninitialized local variable will result in a compile-time error.
[src:java/datatypes] You may have noticed that the `new` keyword isn't used when initializing a variable of a primitive type.
[src:java/datatypes] Primitive types are special data types built into the language; they are not objects created from a class.
[src:java/datatypes] A *literal* is the source code representation of a fixed value; literals are represented directly in your code without requiring computation.
[src:java/datatypes] An integer literal is of type `long` if it ends with the letter `L` or `l`; otherwise it is of type `int`.
[src:java/datatypes] It is recommended that you use the upper case letter `L` because the lower case letter `l` is hard to distinguish from the digit `1`.
[src:java/datatypes] Values of the integral types `byte`, `short`, `int`, and `long` can be created from `int` literals.
[src:java/datatypes] Values of type `long` that exceed the range of `int` can be created from `long` literals.
[src:java/datatypes] For general-purpose programming, the decimal system is likely to be the only number system you'll ever use.
[src:java/datatypes] However, if you need to use another number system, the following example shows the correct syntax.
[src:java/datatypes] A floating-point literal is of type `float` if it ends with the letter `F` or `f`; otherwise its type is `double` and it can optionally end with the letter `D` or `d`.
[src:java/datatypes] The floating point types (`float` and `double`) can also be expressed using E or e (for scientific notation), F or f (32-bit float literal) and D or d (64-bit double literal; this is the default and by convention is omitted).
[src:java/datatypes] Literals of types `char` and `String` may contain any Unicode (UTF-16) characters.
[src:java/datatypes] If your editor and file system allow it, you can use such characters directly in your code.
[src:java/datatypes] If not, you can use a "Unicode escape" such as `'\u0108'` (capital C with circumflex), or `"S\u00ED Se\u00F1or"` (Sí Señor in Spanish).
[src:java/datatypes] Always use 'single quotes' for `char` literals and "double quotes" for `String` literals.
[src:java/datatypes] Unicode escape sequences may be used elsewhere in a program (such as in field names, for example), not just in `char` or `String` literals.
[src:java/datatypes] The Java programming language also supports a few special escape sequences for `char` and `String` literals: `\b` (backspace), `\t` (tab), `\n` (line feed), `\f` (form feed), `\r` (carriage return), `\"` (double quote), `\'` (single quote), and `\\` (backslash).
[src:java/datatypes] There's also a special `null` literal that can be used as a value for any reference type.
[src:java/datatypes] `null` may be assigned to any variable, except variables of primitive types.
[src:java/datatypes] There's little you can do with a `null` value beyond testing for its presence.
[src:java/datatypes] Therefore, `null` is often used in programs as a marker to indicate that some object is unavailable.
[src:java/datatypes] Finally, there's also a special kind of literal called a *class literal*, formed by taking a type name and appending "`.class"`; for example, `String.class`.
[src:java/datatypes] This refers to the object (of type `Class`) that represents the type itself.
[src:java/datatypes] In Java SE 7 and later, any number of underscore characters (`_`) can appear anywhere between digits in a numerical literal.
[src:java/datatypes] This feature enables you, for example. to separate groups of digits in numeric literals, which can improve the readability of your code.
[src:java/datatypes] For instance, if your code contains numbers with many digits, you can use an underscore character to separate digits in groups of three, similar to how you would use a punctuation mark like a comma, or a space, as a separator.
[src:java/definition] is an event, which occurs during the execution of a program, that disrupts the normal flow of the program's instructions.
[src:java/definition] When an error occurs within a method, the method creates an object and hands it off to the runtime system.
[src:java/definition] The object, called an *exception object*, contains information about the error, including its type and the state of the program when the error occurred.
[src:java/definition] Creating an exception object and handing it to the runtime system is called *throwing an exception*.
[src:java/definition] After a method throws an exception, the runtime system attempts to find something to handle it.
[src:java/definition] The set of possible "somethings" to handle the exception is the ordered list of methods that had been called to get to the method where the error occurred.
[src:java/definition] The list of methods is known as the *call stack* (see the next figure).
[src:java/definition] The runtime system searches the call stack for a method that contains a block of code that can handle the exception.
[src:java/definition] This block of code is called an *exception handler*.
[src:java/definition] The search begins with the method in which the error occurred and proceeds through the call stack in the reverse order in which the methods were called.
[src:java/definition] When an appropriate handler is found, the runtime system passes the exception to the handler.
[src:java/definition] An exception handler is considered appropriate if the type of the exception object thrown matches the type that can be handled by the handler.
[src:java/definition] The exception handler chosen is said to *catch the exception*.
[src:java/definition] If the runtime system exhaustively searches all the methods on the call stack without finding an appropriate exception handler, as shown in the next figure, the runtime system (and, consequently, the program) terminates.
[src:java/definition] Searching the call stack for the exception handler.
[src:java/definition] Using exceptions to manage errors has some advantages over traditional error-management techniques.
[src:java/definition] You can learn more in the Advantages of Exceptions section.
[src:java/generics-types] A *generic type* is a generic class or interface that is parameterized over types.
[src:java/generics-types] The following Box class will be modified to demonstrate the concept.
[src:java/generics-types] Begin by examining a non-generic Box class that operates on objects of any type.
[src:java/generics-types] Since its methods accept or return an Object, you are free to pass in whatever you want, provided that it is not one of the primitive types.
[src:java/generics-types] There is no way to verify, at compile time, how the class is used.
[src:java/generics-types] One part of the code may place an Integer in the box and expect to get Integers out of it, while another part of the code may mistakenly pass in a String, resulting in a runtime error.
[src:java/generics-types] The type parameter section, delimited by angle brackets (<>), follows the class name.
[src:java/generics-types] It specifies the *type parameters* (also called *type variables*) T1, T2, ..., and Tn.
[src:java/generics-types] To update the Box class to use generics, you create a *generic type declaration* by changing the code "public class Box" to "public class Box<T>".
[src:java/generics-types] This introduces the type variable, T, that can be used anywhere inside the class.
[src:java/generics-types] As you can see, all occurrences of Object are replaced by T.
[src:java/generics-types] A type variable can be any **non-primitive** type you specify: any class type, any interface type, any array type, or even another type variable.
[src:java/generics-types] This same technique can be applied to create generic interfaces.
[src:java/generics-types] By convention, type parameter names are single, uppercase letters.
[src:java/generics-types] This stands in sharp contrast to the variable naming conventions that you already know about, and with good reason: Without this convention, it would be difficult to tell the difference between a type variable and an ordinary class or interface name.
[src:java/generics-types] You'll see these names used throughout the Java SE API and the rest of this lesson.
[src:java/generics-types] You can think of a generic type invocation as being similar to an ordinary method invocation, but instead of passing an argument to a method, you are passing a *type argument* — Integer in this case — to the Box class itself.
[src:java/generics-types] Many developers use the terms "type parameter" and "type argument" interchangeably, but these terms are not the same.
[src:java/generics-types] When coding, one provides type arguments in order to create a parameterized type.
[src:java/generics-types] This lesson observes this definition when using these terms.
[src:java/generics-types] Like any other variable declaration, this code does not actually create a new Box object.
[src:java/generics-types] It simply declares that integerBox will hold a reference to a "Box of Integer", which is how Box<Integer> is read.
[src:java/generics-types] An invocation of a generic type is generally known as a *parameterized type*.
[src:java/generics-types] In Java SE 7 and later, you can replace the type arguments required to invoke the constructor of a generic class with an empty set of type arguments (<>) as long as the compiler can determine, or infer, the type arguments from the context.
[src:java/generics-types] This pair of angle brackets, <>, is informally called *the diamond*.
[src:java/generics-types] For more information on diamond notation and type inference, see Type Inference.
[src:java/generics-types] As mentioned previously, a generic class can have multiple type parameters.
[src:java/generics-types] The code, new OrderedPair<String, Integer>, instantiates K as a String and V as an Integer.
[src:java/generics-types] Therefore, the parameter types of OrderedPair's constructor are String and Integer, respectively.
[src:java/generics-types] Due to autoboxing, it is valid to pass a String and an int to the class.
[src:java/generics-types] To create a generic interface, follow the same conventions as for creating a generic class.
[src:java/generics-types] You can also substitute a type parameter (that is, K or V) with a parameterized type (that is, List<String>).
[src:java/interfaces-index] The *core collection interfaces* encapsulate different types of collections, which are shown in the figure below.
[src:java/interfaces-index] These interfaces allow collections to be manipulated independently of the details of their representation.
[src:java/interfaces-index] Core collection interfaces are the foundation of the Java Collections Framework.
[src:java/interfaces-index] As you can see in the following figure, the core collection interfaces form a hierarchy.
[src:java/interfaces-index] A `Set` is a special kind of `Collection`, a `SortedSet` is a special kind of `Set`, and so forth.
[src:java/interfaces-index] Note also that the hierarchy consists of two distinct trees — a `Map` is not a true `Collection`.
[src:java/interfaces-index] Note that all the core collection interfaces are generic.
[src:java/interfaces-index] For example, this is the declaration of the `Collection` interface.
[src:java/interfaces-index] The `<E>` syntax tells you that the interface is generic.
[src:java/interfaces-index] When you declare a `Collection` instance you can *and should* specify the type of object contained in the collection.
[src:java/interfaces-index] Specifying the type allows the compiler to verify (at compile-time) that the type of object you put into the collection is correct, thus reducing errors at runtime.
[src:java/interfaces-index] For information on generic types, see the Generics (Updated) lesson.
[src:java/interfaces-index] When you understand how to use these interfaces, you will know most of what there is to know about the Java Collections Framework.
[src:java/interfaces-index] This chapter discusses general guidelines for effective use of the interfaces, including when to use which interface.
[src:java/interfaces-index] You'll also learn programming idioms for each interface to help you get the most out of it.
[src:java/interfaces-index] To keep the number of core collection interfaces manageable, the Java platform doesn't provide separate interfaces for each variant of each collection type.
[src:java/interfaces-index] (Such variants might include immutable, fixed-size, and append-only.) Instead, the modification operations in each interface are designated *optional* — a given implementation may elect not to support all operations.
[src:java/interfaces-index] If an unsupported operation is invoked, a collection throws an `UnsupportedOperationException`.
[src:java/interfaces-index] Implementations are responsible for documenting which of the optional operations they support.
[src:java/interfaces-index] All of the Java platform's general-purpose implementations support all of the optional operations.
[src:java/interfaces-index] To understand how the sorted interfaces maintain the order of their elements, see the Object Ordering section.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:java/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:java/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:java/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:java/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:java/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:java/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:java/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:java/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:java/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:java/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:java/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:java/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:java/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:java/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:java/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:java/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:java/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:java/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:java/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Oracle released the last zero-cost public update for the legacy version Java 8 LTS in January 2019 for commercial use, although it will otherwise still support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Other vendors such as Adoptium continue to offer free builds of OpenJDK's long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:java/java-programming-language] These builds may include additional security patches and bug fixes.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:java/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:java/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:java/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:java/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:java/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:java/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:java/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:java/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:java/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:java/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:java/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:java/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:java/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:java/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:java/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:java/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:java/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:java/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:java/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
[src:java/java-programming-language] In prior versions of Java, such as Java 8, the Parallel Garbage Collector was used as the default garbage collector.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Having solved the memory management problem does not relieve the programmer of the burden of handling properly other kinds of resources, like network or database connections, file handles, etc., especially in the presence of exceptions.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The syntax of Java is largely influenced by C++ and C.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, which combines the syntax for structured, generic, and object-oriented programming, Java was built almost exclusively as an object-oriented language.
[src:java/java-programming-language] All code is written inside classes, and every data item is an object, with the exception of the primitive data types, (i.e. integers, floating-point numbers, boolean values, and characters), which are not objects for performance reasons.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, Java does not support operator overloading or multiple inheritance for classes, though multiple inheritance is supported for interfaces.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java uses comments similar to those of C++.
[src:java/java-programming-language] There are three different styles of comments: a single line style marked with two slashes (`//`), a multiple line style opened with `/*` and closed with `*/`, and the Javadoc commenting style opened with `/**` and closed with `*/`.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The Javadoc style of commenting allows the user to run the Javadoc executable to create documentation for the program and can be read by some integrated development environments (IDEs) such as Eclipse to allow developers to access documentation within the IDE.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java applets were programs embedded in other applications, mainly in web pages displayed in web browsers.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The Java applet API was deprecated with the release of Java 9 in 2017.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Java servlet technology provides Web developers with a simple, consistent mechanism for extending the functionality of a Web server and for accessing existing business systems.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Servlets are server-side Java EE components that generate responses to requests from clients.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Most of the time, this means generating HTML pages in response to HTTP requests, although there are a number of other standard servlet classes available, for example for WebSocket communication.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Typical implementations of these APIs on Application Servers or Servlet Containers use a standard servlet for handling all interactions with the HTTP requests and responses that delegate to the web service methods for the actual business logic.
[src:java/java-programming-language] JavaServer Pages (JSP) are server-side Java EE components that generate responses, typically HTML pages, to HTTP requests from clients.
[src:java/java-programming-language] JSPs embed Java code in an HTML page by using the special delimiters `<%` and `%>`.
[src:java/java-programming-language] A JSP is compiled to a Java *servlet*, a Java application in its own right, the first time it is accessed.
[src:java/java-programming-language] After that, the generated servlet creates the response.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Swing is a graphical user interface library for the Java SE platform.
[src:java/java-programming-language] It is possible to specify a different look and feel through the pluggable look and feel system of Swing.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Clones of Windows, GTK+, and Motif are supplied by Sun.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Apple also provides an Aqua look and feel for macOS.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Where prior implementations of these looks and feels may have been considered lacking, Swing in Java SE 6 addresses this problem by using more native GUI widget drawing routines of the underlying platforms.
[src:java/java-programming-language] JavaFX is a software platform for creating and delivering desktop applications, as well as rich web applications that can run across a wide variety of devices.
[src:java/java-programming-language] JavaFX is intended to replace Swing as the standard graphical user interface (GUI) library for Java SE, but since JDK 11 JavaFX has not been in the core JDK and is instead available as a separate module.
[src:java/java-programming-language] JavaFX has support for desktop computers and web browsers on Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:java/java-programming-language] JavaFX does not have support for native OS look and feels.
[src:java/java-programming-language] In 2004, generics were added to the Java language, as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Prior to the introduction of generics, each variable declaration had to be of a specific type.
[src:java/java-programming-language] For container classes, for example, this is a problem because there is no easy way to create a container that accepts only specific types of objects.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Either the container operates on all subtypes of a class or interface, usually `Object`, or a different container class has to be created for each contained class.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Generics allow compile-time type checking without having to create many container classes, each containing almost identical code.
[src:java/java-programming-language] In addition to enabling more efficient code, certain runtime exceptions are prevented from occurring, by issuing compile-time errors.
[src:java/java-programming-language] If Java prevented all runtime type errors (`ClassCastException`s) from occurring, it would be type safe.
[src:java/java-programming-language] In 2016, the type system of Java was proven unsound in that it is possible to use generics to construct classes and methods that allow assignment of an instance of one class to a variable of another unrelated class.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Such code is accepted by the compiler, but fails at run time with a class cast exception.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Criticisms directed at Java include the implementation of generics, speed, the handling of unsigned numbers, the implementation of floating-point arithmetic, and a history of security vulnerabilities in the primary Java VM implementation HotSpot.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Developers have criticized the complexity and verbosity of the Java Persistence API (JPA), a standard part of Java EE.
[src:java/java-programming-language] This has led to increased adoption of higher-level abstractions like Spring Data JPA, which aims to simplify database operations and reduce boilerplate code.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The growing popularity of such frameworks suggests limitations in the standard JPA implementation's ease-of-use for modern Java development.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The Java Class Library is the standard library, developed to support application development in Java.
[src:java/java-programming-language] It is controlled by Oracle in cooperation with others through the Java Community Process program.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Companies or individuals participating in this process can influence the design and development of the APIs.
[src:java/java-programming-language] This process has been a subject of controversy during the 2010s.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Javadoc is a comprehensive documentation system, created by Sun Microsystems.
[src:java/java-programming-language] It provides developers with an organized system for documenting their code.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Javadoc comments have an extra asterisk at the beginning, i.e. the delimiters are `/**` and `*/`, whereas the normal multi-line comments in Java are delimited by `/*` and `*/`, and single-line comments start with `//`.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Oracle Corporation owns the official implementation of the Java SE platform, due to its acquisition of Sun Microsystems on January 27, 2010.
[src:java/java-programming-language] This implementation is based on the original implementation of Java by Sun.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The Oracle implementation is available for Windows, macOS, Linux, and Solaris.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Because Java lacks any formal standardization recognized by Ecma International, ISO/IEC, ANSI, or other third-party standards organizations, the Oracle implementation is the de facto standard.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Oracle has also released GraalVM, a high performance Java dynamic compiler and interpreter.
[src:java/java-programming-language] OpenJDK is another Java SE implementation that is licensed under the GNU GPL.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The implementation started when Sun began releasing the Java source code under the GPL.
[src:java/java-programming-language] As of Java SE 7, OpenJDK is the official Java reference implementation.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The goal of Java is to make all implementations of Java compatible.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Historically, Sun's trademark license for usage of the Java brand insists that all implementations be *compatible*.
[src:java/java-programming-language] This resulted in a legal dispute with Microsoft after Sun claimed that the Microsoft implementation did not support Java remote method invocation (RMI) or Java Native Interface (JNI) and had added platform-specific features of their own.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Sun sued in 1997, and, in 2001, won a settlement of US$20 million, as well as a court order enforcing the terms of the license from Sun.
[src:java/java-programming-language] As a result, Microsoft no longer ships Java with Windows.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Platform-independent Java is essential to Java EE, and an even more rigorous validation is required to certify an implementation.
[src:java/java-programming-language] This environment enables portable server-side applications.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The Java programming language requires the presence of a software platform in order for compiled programs to be executed.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Oracle supplies the Java platform for use with Java.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The Android SDK is an alternative software platform, used primarily for developing Android applications with its own GUI system.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The Java language is a key pillar in Android, an open source mobile operating system.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Although Android, built on the Linux kernel, is written largely in C, the Android SDK uses the Java language as the basis for Android applications but does not use any of its standard GUI, SE, ME or other established Java standards.
[src:java/java-programming-language] The bytecode language supported by the Android SDK is incompatible with JVM bytecode and runs on its own virtual machine, optimized for low-memory devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Depending on the Android version, the bytecode is either interpreted by the Dalvik virtual machine or compiled into native code by the Android Runtime.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Android does not provide the full Java SE standard library, although the Android SDK does include an independent implementation of a large subset of it.
[src:java/java-programming-language] It supports Java 6 and some Java 7 features, offering an implementation compatible with the standard library (Apache Harmony).
[src:java/java-programming-language] The use of Java-related technology in Android led to a legal dispute between Oracle and Google.
[src:java/java-programming-language] On May 7, 2012, a San Francisco jury found that if APIs could be copyrighted, then Google had infringed Oracle's copyrights by the use of Java in Android devices.
[src:java/java-programming-language] District Judge William Alsup ruled on May 31, 2012, that APIs cannot be copyrighted, but this was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in May 2014.
[src:java/java-programming-language] On May 26, 2016, the district court decided in favor of Google, ruling the copyright infringement of the Java API in Android constitutes fair use.
[src:java/java-programming-language] In March 2018, this ruling was overturned by the Appeals Court, which sent down the case of determining the damages to federal court in San Francisco.
[src:java/java-programming-language] Google filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the Supreme Court of the United States in January 2019 to challenge the two rulings that were made by the Appeals Court in Oracle's favor.
[src:java/java-programming-language] On April 5, 2021, the Court ruled 6–2 in Google's favor, that its use of Java APIs should be considered fair use.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] A **Java virtual machine** (**JVM**) is a virtual machine that enables a computer to run Java programs as well as programs written in other languages, other languages referred to as JVM languages that are also compiled to Java bytecode.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The JVM is detailed by a specification that formally describes what is required in a JVM implementation.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Having a specification ensures interoperability of Java programs across different implementations so that program authors using the Java Development Kit (JDK) need not worry about idiosyncrasies of the underlying hardware platform.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The JVM reference implementation is developed by the OpenJDK project as open source code and includes a JIT compiler called HotSpot.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The commercially supported Java releases available from Oracle are based on the OpenJDK runtime.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Eclipse OpenJ9 is another open source JVM for OpenJDK.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The Java virtual machine is an abstract (virtual) computer defined by a specification.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] It is a part of the Java Runtime Environment.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The garbage collection algorithm used and any internal optimization of the Java virtual machine instructions (their translation into machine code) are not specified.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The main reason for this omission is to not unnecessarily constrain implementers.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Any Java application can be run only inside some concrete implementation of the abstract specification of the Java virtual machine.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Starting with Java Platform, Standard Edition (J2SE) 5.0, changes to the JVM specification have been developed under the Java Community Process as JSR 924.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] As of 2006, changes to the specification to support changes proposed to the class file format (JSR 202) are being done as a maintenance release of JSR 924.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The most commonly used Java virtual machine is Oracle's HotSpot.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Oracle owns the Java trademark and may allow its use to certify implementation suites as fully compatible with Oracle's specification.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Java's design philosophy revolves around the assumption of a garbage collector.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Unlike languages such as C++ and Rust, deterministic memory management through a `delete` keyword (as in C++) is not possible.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Even introducing such a feature is not possible, due to a lack of ownership, aside from using sun.misc.Unsafe or through java.lang.foreign to allocate/deallocate memory outside the Java heap.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Due to Java primarily using heap-based allocation, objects are stored as references, and deletion would result in dangling pointers.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The JVM operates on specific types of data as specified in Java Virtual Machine specifications.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The data types can be divided into primitive types (integer and floating-point values) and reference types.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] `long` and `double` types, which are 64-bits, are supported natively, but consume two units of storage in a frame's local variables or operand stack, since each unit is 32 bits.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] `boolean`, `byte`, `short`, and `char` types are all sign-extended (except `char` which is zero-extended) and operated on as 32-bit integers, the same as `int` types.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The smaller types only have a few type-specific instructions for loading, storing, and type conversion.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] `boolean` is operated on as 8-bit `byte` values, with 0 representing `false` and 1 representing `true`.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] (Although `boolean` has been treated as a type since *The Java Virtual Machine Specification, Second Edition* clarified this issue, in compiled and executed code there is little difference between a `boolean` and a `byte` except for name mangling in method signatures and the type of Boolean arrays.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] `boolean`s in method signatures are mangled as `Z` while `byte`s are mangled as `B`.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Boolean arrays carry the type `boolean[]` but use 8 bits per element, and the JVM has no built-in capability to pack booleans into a bit array, so except for the type they perform and behave the same as `byte` arrays.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The JVM has a garbage-collected heap for storing objects and arrays.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Code, constants, and other class data are stored in the "method area".
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The method area is logically part of the heap, but implementations may treat the method area separately from the heap, and for example might not garbage collect it.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Each JVM thread also has its own call stack (called a "Java Virtual Machine stack" for clarity), which stores frames.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] A new frame is created each time a method is called, and the frame is destroyed when that method exits.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Each frame provides an "operand stack" and an array of "local variables".
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The operand stack is used for operands to run computations and for receiving the return value of a called method, while local variables serve the same purpose as registers and are also used to pass method arguments.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Thus, the JVM is both a stack machine and a register machine.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] In practice, HotSpot eliminates every stack besides the native thread/call stack even when running in Interpreted mode, as its Templating Interpreter technically functions as a compiler.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The JVM uses references and stack/array indexes to address data; it does not use byte addressing like most physical machines do, so it does not neatly fit the usual categorization of 32-bit or 64-bit machines.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] In one sense, it could be classified as a 32-bit machine, since this is the size of the largest value it natively stores: a 32-bit integer or floating-point value or a 32-bit reference.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Because a reference is 32 bits, each program is limited to at most 232 unique references and therefore at most 232 objects.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] However, each object can be more than one byte large, and potentially *very* large; the largest possible object is an array of `long` of length 231 - 1 which would consume 16 GiB of memory, and there could potentially be 232 of these if there were enough memory available.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] This results in upper bounds that are more comparable to a typical 64-bit byte-addressable machine.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] A JVM implementation can be designed to run on a processor that natively uses any bit width as long as it correctly implements the integer (8-, 16-, 32-, and 64-bit) and floating-point (32- and 64-bit) math that the JVM requires.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Depending on the method used to implement references (native pointers, compressed pointers, or an indirection table), this can limit the number of objects to less than the theoretical maximum.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] A JVM language is any language with functions that can be expressed in a valid class file, which can be hosted by a JVM.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] A class file contains JVM instructions (JVM bytecode), a symbol table, and other ancillary information.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The class file format is the hardware- and operating system-independent binary format used to represent compiled classes and interfaces.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] There are several JVM languages, both older established languages ported to JVM, and much newer from-scratch languages.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] JRuby and Jython may be the best known ports of older languages, i.e., Ruby and Python respectively.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Of the new from-scratch languages created to compile to Java bytecode, Clojure, Groovy, Scala and Kotlin may be the most popular.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] A notable feature of the JVM languages is their language interoperability, they are compatible with each other, so that, for example, Scala libraries can be used with Java programs and vice versa.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Java 7 JVM implements *JSR 292: Supporting Dynamically Typed Languages* on the Java Platform, a new feature which supports dynamically typed languages in the JVM.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] This feature is developed within the Da Vinci Machine project whose mission is to extend the JVM so that it supports languages other than Java.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] One of the organizational units of JVM byte code is a class.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] A class loader implementation must be able to recognize and load anything that conforms to the Java class file format.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Any implementation is free to recognize other binary forms besides *class* files, but it must recognize *class* files.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Initialization: invokes Java code that initializes class variables to their proper starting values.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] In general, there are three types of class loader: bootstrap class loader, extension class loader and System / Application class loader.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Every Java virtual machine implementation must have a bootstrap class loader that is capable of loading trusted classes, as well as an extension class loader or application class loader.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The Java virtual machine specification does not specify how a class loader should locate classes.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Each particular host operating system needs its own implementation of the JVM and runtime.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] These JVMs interpret the bytecode semantically the same way, but the actual implementation may be different.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] More complex than just emulating bytecode is compatibly and efficiently implementing the Java core API that must be mapped to each host operating system.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] These instructions operate on a set of common abstracted data types rather the native data types of any specific instruction set architecture.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Furthermore, common programmer errors that often led to data corruption or unpredictable behavior such as accessing off the end of an array or using an uninitialized pointer are not allowed to occur.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Several features of Java combine to provide this safety, including the class model, the garbage-collected heap, and the verifier.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The JVM verifies all bytecode before it is executed.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The first two of these checks take place primarily during the verification step that occurs when a class is loaded and made eligible for use.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The third is primarily performed dynamically, when data items or methods of a class are first accessed by another class.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The verifier permits only some bytecode sequences in valid programs, e.g. a jump (branch) instruction can only target an instruction within the same method.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Furthermore, the verifier ensures that any given instruction operates on a fixed stack location, allowing the JIT compiler to transform stack accesses into fixed register accesses.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Because of this, that the JVM is a stack architecture does not imply a speed penalty for emulation on register-based architectures when using a JIT compiler.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] In the face of the code-verified JVM architecture, it makes no difference to a JIT compiler whether it gets named imaginary registers or imaginary stack positions that must be allocated to the target architecture's registers.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] In fact, code verification makes the JVM different from a classic stack architecture, of which efficient emulation with a JIT compiler is more complicated and typically carried out by a slower interpreter.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Additionally, the Interpreter used by the default JVM is a special type known as a Template Interpreter, which translates bytecode directly to native, register based machine language rather than emulate a stack like a typical interpreter.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Another instance of a stack architecture being merely a specification and implemented in a register based virtual machine is the Common Language Runtime.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The original specification for the bytecode verifier used natural language that was incomplete or incorrect in some respects.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] A number of attempts have been made to specify the JVM as a formal system.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] By doing this, the security of current JVM implementations can more thoroughly be analyzed, and potential security exploits prevented.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] It will also be possible to optimize the JVM by skipping unnecessary safety checks, if the application being run is proven to be safe.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] A virtual machine architecture allows very fine-grained control over the actions that code within the machine is permitted to take.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] It assumes the code is "semantically" correct, that is, it successfully passed the (formal) bytecode verifier process, materialized by a tool, possibly off-board the virtual machine.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] This is designed to allow safe execution of untrusted code from remote sources, a model used by Java applets, and other secure code downloads.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Once bytecode-verified, the downloaded code runs in a restricted "sandbox", which is designed to protect the user from misbehaving or malicious code.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] As an addition to the bytecode verification process, publishers can purchase a certificate with which to digitally sign applets as safe, giving them permission to ask the user to break out of the sandbox and access the local file system, clipboard, execute external pieces of software, or network.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] For each hardware architecture a different Java bytecode interpreter is needed.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] When a computer has a Java bytecode interpreter, it can run any Java bytecode program, and the same program can be run on any computer that has such an interpreter.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] When Java bytecode is executed by an interpreter, the execution will always be slower than the execution of the same program compiled into native machine language.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] This problem is mitigated by just-in-time (JIT) compilers for executing Java bytecode.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] A JIT compiler may translate Java bytecode into native machine language while executing the program.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The translated parts of the program can then be executed much more quickly than they could be interpreted.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] This technique gets applied to those parts of a program frequently executed.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] This way a JIT compiler can significantly speed up the overall execution time.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] There is no necessary connection between the Java programming language and Java bytecode.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] A program written in Java can be compiled directly into the machine language of a real computer and programs written in other languages than Java can be compiled into Java bytecode.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Java bytecode is intended to be platform-independent and secure.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Some JVM implementations do not include an interpreter, but consist only of a just-in-time compiler.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Java 22 introduces the Foreign Function and Memory API, which can be seen as the successor to Java Native Interface.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Native methods are enable by JNI to handle situations when an application cannot be written entirely in the Java programming language, e.g. when the standard Java class library does not support the platform-specific features or program library.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The JNI framework lets a native method use Java objects in the same way that Java code uses these objects.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] A native method can create Java objects and then inspect and use these objects to perform its tasks.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] A native method can also inspect and use objects created by Java application code.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] JNI also allows direct access to assembly code, without even going through a C bridge.[3] Accessing Java applications from assembly is possible in the same way.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] At the start of the Java platform's lifetime, the JVM was marketed as a web technology for creating Rich Web Applications.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] As of 2018, most web browsers and operating systems bundling web browsers do not ship with a Java plug-in, nor do they permit side-loading any non-Flash plug-in.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The Java browser plugin was deprecated in JDK 9.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The NPAPI Java browser plug-in was designed to allow the JVM to execute so-called Java applets embedded into HTML pages.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] For browsers with the plug-in installed, the applet is allowed to draw into a rectangular region on the page assigned to it.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Because the plug-in includes a JVM, Java applets are not restricted to the Java programming language; any language targeting the JVM may run in the plug-in.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] A restricted set of APIs allow applets access to the user's microphone or 3D acceleration, although applets are not able to modify the page outside its rectangular region.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Adobe Flash Player, the main competing technology, works in the same way in this respect.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] As of June 2015 according to W3Techs, Java applet and Silverlight use had fallen to 0.1% each for all web sites, while Flash had fallen to 10.8%.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Since May 2016, JavaPoly allows users to import unmodified Java libraries, and invoke them directly from JavaScript.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] JavaPoly allows websites to use unmodified Java libraries, even if the user does not have Java installed on their computer.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] With the continuing improvements in JavaScript execution speed, combined with the increased use of mobile devices whose web browsers do not implement support for plugins, there are efforts to target those users through transpilation to JavaScript.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] It is possible to either transpile the source code or JVM bytecode to JavaScript.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Compiling the JVM bytecode, which is universal across JVM languages, allows building upon the language's existing compiler to bytecode.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] The main JVM bytecode to JavaScript transpilers are TeaVM, the compiler contained in Dragome Web SDK, Bck2Brwsr, and j2js-compiler.
[src:java/java-virtual-machine] Leading transpilers from JVM languages to JavaScript include the Java-to-JavaScript transpiler contained in Google Web Toolkit, J2CL, Clojurescript (Clojure), GrooScript (Apache Groovy), Scala.js (Scala) and others.
[src:java/nutsandbolts-flow] The statements inside your source files are generally executed from top to bottom, in the order that they appear.
[src:java/nutsandbolts-flow] *Control flow statements*, however, break up the flow of execution by employing decision making, looping, and branching, enabling your program to *conditionally* execute particular blocks of code.
[src:java/nutsandbolts-flow] This section describes the decision-making statements (`if-then`, `if-then-else`, `switch`), the looping statements (`for`, `while`, `do-while`), and the branching statements (`break`, `continue`, `return`) supported by the Java programming language.
[src:java/threads] Each thread is associated with an instance of the class `Thread`.
[src:java/threads] There are two basic strategies for using `Thread` objects to create a concurrent application.
[src:java/threads] This section documents the use of `Thread` objects.
[src:java/threads] Executors are discussed with other high-level concurrency objects.
